Notopodial postchaetal lamellae short and triangular on chaetiger 2 (
Fig. 3A, B
); elongated, subtriangular, with short, blunt tips on chaetigers 3–10 (
Fig. 3A, B, D, E
); progressively decreasing in size, becoming shorter, broader and oval (
holotype
11) on chaetigers 11–12 (
Fig. 3G
); rounded and progressively decreasing in size from chaetiger 13; eventually becoming small, rounded lobes (
Fig. 3H
). Notopodial postchaetal lamellae joined across dorsum on chaetigers 10–17 (
10–16 in
holotype
) forming low crests (
Fig. 3G
). Ventral edges of notopodial lamellae and dorsal edges of neuropodial lamellae not touching on any chaetigers. Notopodial prechaetal lamellae small, rounded in anterior region, not fused basally with notopodial postchaetal lamellae (
Fig. 3
D–G).

Neuropodial postchaetal lamellae oval-shaped on chaetiger 2, with ventral edge broader than dorsal edge (
Fig. 3B
); lamellae largest on chaetigers 3–5, approximately rectangular in shape (higher than broad), with rounded edges (
Fig. 3B, D, E
), and on chaetiger 6 becoming more rounded on posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 3F
). Anterior and middle neuropodial prechaetal lamellae small, rounded (
Fig. 3A, B
, C–F). Ventrolateral interparapodial pouches absent.

Notopodial capillaries on anterior chaetigers arranged in two rows: anterior row short, smooth, alimbate (

Fig. 
3I

); posterior row longer, thinner, slightly granulated, alimbate (
Fig. 3J
). Notopodial capillaries on middle chaetigers arranged in two rows: anterior row short, smooth, alimbate (
Fig. 3K
); posterior row slightly granulated, alimbate, with long pointed tips (
Fig. 3L
). Posterior chaetigers with long, slender, smooth, alimbate chaetae (
Fig. 3M
). Neuropodial capillaries arranged in a tuft on chaetiger 1; from chaetiger 2 arranged in two rows; all capillaries with same structure as notopodial chaetae. Sabre chaetae on neuropodia from chaetigers 12–16 (
14 in
holotype
), up to two per fascicle, each chaeta stout, distinctly curved, basally smooth, heavily granulated medially and distally, without sheaths (
Fig. 3N
). Neuropodial hooded hooks (
Fig. 3O
) from chaetigers 13–17 (
holotype
15), up to eight per fascicle, accompanied by thin, alimbate capillaries (
Fig. 3P
). Neuropodial hooks with five pairs of small teeth above large main fang, and small secondary hoods (
Fig. 3Q
). Notopodial hooded hooks from chaetigers 32–35, up to two per fascicle, with four pairs of small teeth above large main tooth, and small secondary hoods.
